    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "\r\nThanks @gnidan!\r\n\r\nI don't see why you don't want to be tied to npm...\r\n\r\nSince it is installed via npm, it pretty much is. Having this is in the dev dependencies of the project would also make it easier for developers to more easily use a consistent version of truffle.\r\n\r\nThe default license that npm uses is ISC so I think that would be fine.\r\n\r\nI think this would be a decent one to include in truffle init:\r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n  \"name\": \"<new truffle project>\",\r\n  \"version\": \"0.0.1\",\r\n  \"description\": \"\",\r\n  \"main\": \"\",\r\n  \"scripts\": {\r\n    \"start\": \"truffle develop\",\r\n    \"test\": \"truffle test\"\r\n  },\r\n  \"author\": \"\",\r\n  \"license\": \"ISC\",\r\n  \"devDependencies\": {\r\n    \"truffle\": \"^5.3.10\"\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf for some reason the user doesn't want to the package.json then he or she can delete it. ðŸ˜‰\r\n\r\nBut once you get deep into developing with truffle you end up wanting to use truffle-assert, nodemon, etc. and realize that you really need a package.json at the very least for keeping track of your dependencies.\r\n\r\n",
